column3: Kara : A social network to reduce the world's inequality
column5: Houda Nait El Barj, Julio Ballista, Jhonatan Ewunetie, Neena Dolores Romero, Rayan Albraidi
column7:
Kara aims to revolutionize the donation experience of people worldwide. 

Kara is designed as a social network that connects donors (mentors) with people in need of financial help (protégés). Protégés and mentors are matched based on their preferences and can form a personal relationship through private messaging and interaction via social feeds. Mentors can directly send money to their protégés, helping them achieve their basic needs. Once that need is met, mentors get notified via a picture, call or video, which allows them to directly see the impact of their donation. 

Kara aims to increase worldwide donations by providing an intuitive platform with mechanisms designed to incentivize donors to give more.

column7: Our overarching goal is to explore the possibilities of camera mechanics in GHA and develop a camera feature that is engaging to users. Aside from the traditional expectations of a camera to take pictures and store them in an album, we also want to leverage the reality-defying aspect of VR by implementing features that allow users to collect and replicate artifacts using the camera. The test and implementation of these ‘non-traditional’ features will be realized through a museum-themed outer game loop where the player can curate a museum by visiting new sites, taking pictures and collecting artifacts.

column3: ARCH: A VR Stonehenge Storytelling Experience
column4: Education, Games, Virtual or Augmented Reality
column5: Shana Hadi, Jonathan Kula, Lina Fang, Jiahui Chen
column6: N/A, as circumstances permit re: international travel!
column7:
Fetch your love for adventure and put on an Oculus Quest 2 headset to embark on a 10-minute archaeology-themed experience at one of the wonders of the world, the prehistoric monument of Stonehenge. In this game, you are a graduate student searching for project inspiration under the guidance of your eccentric professor.
Explore the richly rendered environment, discover historical artifacts, and perhaps even converse with the storytelling spirits of the past. Do you have what it takes to craft your own theory about the mysteries of Stonehenge?
(This was made in collaboration with Meta’s Global Historical Archive.)

column3: Reimagining and Scaling Historical Storytelling in VR (GHA)
column4: Education, Games, Virtual or Augmented Reality, Social
column5: Gizem Incesu, Jessica Chen, Emily Redmond, Nicholas Vo
column7: How can historical experiences in VR be more engaging and better support cultural learning? How do we provide replay value, ie. encourage users to return to explore other sites? How do we scale this process? Our project explores each of these questions, working with Meta’s Global Historical Archive (GHA). We present a personable VR prototype experience, including interactions with culturally relevant characters, and a scalable narrative framework to apply to future historical sites. We also present an immersive VR trivia experience, which solidifies user’s historical knowledge gained through the narrative experience.

column5: Armaun Sanayei, Mac Klinkachorn, Maeghan Tovar, Robbie Selwyn
column7: Today’s students are managing incredibly complex calendars, containing classes, meetings, meals, and assignments.  Blueprint is a calendar-based system that allows students to better manage their time by applying tools that have been used successfully in the project management industry, including kanban timelines, multi-source input, and deep analytics.  With Blueprint, students can manage their static (fixed starting and ending time) as well as continuous (fluid events such as assignments) seamlessly, and receive key insights that can help them better manage their time.  We provide options for students to connect their account with popular apps like Canvas and Outlook, allowing for quick onboarding and use.

column5: Alex Fu, Catherine Huang, Julia Kadie, Nick Mayhew
column7:
Vahana is a phone app designed to help new drivers improve their driving in a fun and engaging way. Think Strava meets Spotify Wrapped for driving.

Vahana allows users to record their driving, and then analyses and rates their drives with a safety score. Vahana also provides monthly statistics on users' driving progress. By recording safety score trends and analytical data, Vahana hopes to enable users to become safer drivers.

column3: Applying Determinantal Point Processes for Sample-efficient Exploration in Recommender Systems
column5: Dhruvik Parikh
column7: The "cold start" or new user problem has long plagued recommender systems. In order to resolve this problem before a user churns, exploration mechanisms are applied to learn the user's preferences in as few interactions as possible. This project introduces a novel exploration mechanism based on determinantal point processes that results in more sample-efficient exploration. It also introduces a standardized testing pipeline for exploration mechanisms based on the MovieLens dataset and a baseline Deep Q-Learning model.

We want to be the social middle ground between Explore Courses and Carta, allowing users to clearly visualize what their and their peers' schedules will look like.

column3: Arla: Augmented Reality Language Learning iOS App
column4: Education, Virtual or Augmented Reality, Mobile
column5: Aaron Schultz, Kimmy Chang, Laikh Tewari, Michelle Xing, Ryota Ray Eki
column7:
Learning a new language is one of the most challenging tasks for people of all ages and backgrounds. Yet, language, since the beginning of human organization, is one of the most reliable bridges to other cultures in an interconnected world.

Translation-based apps such as Duolingo, fail to consider one of the most important metrics to language absorption speed and volume: immersion. 

Arla uses AR technology to address this immersion gap. By using familiar objects in the user’s environment through the phone camera, Arla links the user’s memory of the real world to new terms. This tool will help users build their vocabulary, anywhere they go, in an effective and enduring way.

column7: MethaneSAT is a satellite that will be launched in 2 years to track methane emissions from oil and gas facilities. However, we needed to build a dataset of the locations of the oil and gas facilities using satellite imagery.

column3: Forecasting CO2 emissions on a decarbonizing electrical grid
column5: Peter Maldonado
column6: Prof. Chris Piech, Prof. Jacques de Chalendar, Prof. Inês Azevedo
column7:
To continually monitor decarbonization progress and track emissions in the electricity sector, new tools are needed. In particular, accurate forecasts of grid carbon emissions are essential to real time carbon accounting (for measuring carbon displacement) and a market associated with it. Using years of historical grid data in the US (electricity emissions, demand, generation by source, etc.), we develop models to forecast CO2 emissions from electricity demand and generation. Analyzing these models enables us to understand when predictions are the most difficult. In light of increased renewable energy generation, we also ask whether increased renewable generation is related to worse forecast performance.

This senior project was is sponsored by Prof. Chris Piech. Prof. Jacques de Chalendar and Prof. Inês Azevedo helped frame the research questions and provided guidance.

column3: Transformer for Non-Accidental Trauma Prediction from Electronic Health Records
column5: David Huang, Prof. David Kim (advisor), Prof. Serena Yeung (advisor)
column6: Prof. David Kim (advisor), Prof. Serena Yeung (advisor)
column7: Non-accidental trauma (NAT) includes diagnoses such as domestic violence, assault, poisoning, and abuse. In this project, we developed a transformer-based model that uses electronic health record data to predict future diagnosis of NAT. Our model outperforms XGBoost and current state-of-the-art deep learning methods. Key to its performance was the use of a pretraining task for last visit summarization as well as incorporation of demographic and procedural features.

column3: Efficient and Accurate Integration of Diagnostic Machine Learning Models into Radiology Reporting Workflows
column5: Viswesh Krishna, Morgan Sanchez, Kyle Alford
column7: In recent years, significant strides in the machine learning (ML) for healthcare community have led to the integration of ML models into clinical workflows in a number of areas. AI-based decision support tools typically aim to do two things: improve patient outcomes and reduce provider cost and burden. We study real-world production data from a chest x-ray interpretation aid deployed in Vietnam hospitals and analyze cases of AI-clinician disagreement. Inspired by this real-world data, we hypothesize that while AI-clinician collaborative performance could be improved by directly enhancing the underlying model, other aspects of collaboration are ripe for innovation. In particular, when and how to present model output should be motivated by characteristics such as the expected quality of a given prediction and whether the clinician is expected to agree with it along with clinical significance of the pathology in question. We, therefore, present a novel framework for AI-supported diagnosis using these characteristics, which is expected to mitigate risks of misdiagnosis while simultaneously reducing clinician burden.

column5: Krishnan Nair, Stephanie Hu, Rick Robert, Derian Williams, Adonis Pugh
column7: DAHA is a mobile app that allows Stanford students to sell, rent, and buy goods on campus quickly and efficiently. Our product was inspired by DAHA requests in dorm chats, as well as the need for seniors to sell their belongings before graduating to underclassmen that wish to purchase common goods for their college experience at a cheaper price. We envision this as a marketplace for all Stanford students, which extends the reach of DAHA requests beyond a single dorm. In this marketplace, users can enter items that they are seeking (a DAHA request). All users will have access to the requests, allowing them to see which items are in demand. If they have something being requested and wish to sell it, they can create a DAWA post about their item and name their price. Even if a user doesn't wish to make a DAHA, they can enter the marketplace and see what items are up for sale. By understanding what items are in demand and being requested, we hope to encourage the recycling of goods at Stanford.

column3: Domain-Agnostic Benchmark for Self-Supervised Learning - writing a JAX codebase
column5: Shashank Rammoorthy
column7:
The use of self-supervised learning (SSL) algorithms has been on the rise across the machine learning community. SSL helps models acquire useful information from unlabelled data and then use this information to perform downstream tasks. The common paradigm here is to ‘pretrain’ on a large general dataset and then ‘finetune’ on a more specialized, typically smaller dataset.
The Domain-Agnostic Benchmark for Self-Supervised Learning (DABS) was published in NeurIPS last year, and has served as a benchmark for self-supervised learning algorithms. Specifically, to perform well on DABS, an algorithm must be pretrained on six unlabeled datasets from different domains: natural images, text, speech recordings, medical imaging, multichannel sensor data and image-text pairs.
(Tamkin et al.)
Through this Senior Project, I implemented a system for fast and large scale training of self-supervised learning algorithms with DABS. Specifically, I designed and wrote a JAX codebase for DABS — enabling us to run baseline algorithms on Google Cloud Tensor Processing Units, or TPUs, and have an order of magnitude faster training times.

column3: Enforcing Attention Map Consistency for Unsupervised Finetuning
column5: Max Pike
column6: Ali Mirzazadeh, Krish Maniar, Florian Dubost, Christopher Lee-Messer, Daniel Rubin
column7: In many industry computer vision tasks, large, labeled datasets are hard to come by. Therefore, when it comes to training deep neural networks, they have a hard time learning meaningful representations from the dataset. One way to visualize these models is through calculation of "attention maps" that display which parts of the input were important in making the associated prediction. Attention maps can be calculated in different ways, and as a result, do not always agree with each other. This problem becomes exacerbated when the model is overfitting to a small dataset. As a result, the QIAI lab proposes an unsupervised learning objective to be used as a fine-tuning step, where we calculate attention maps with 2 different algorithms and enforce a similarity metric between them.

column7: “Margaret” is an interactive short story that takes the form of a text conversation between the reader and a chatbot. Through an alternative form of storytelling, this project aims to incorporate user interaction to explore character construction and development in fiction.

column5: Samaksh Goyal, Mark Rau, Doug James
column7:
In this project we aim to establish the relationship between the
construction of an acoustic guitar and the resulting frequency and
amplitude response. The forward modeling problem is to take as
input the physical material parameters and geometry of a guitar
and use FEM methods to perform modal analysis. This part involves
modeling the guitar meshing, elasticity coefficients for the wood,
and different boundary conditions. The inverse problem (the more
interesting case) is to take as input the a user defined “sound” and
find the best parameters for a guitar that would produce such a
sound

column3: DABS 2.0: Improved Datasets, Algorithms, and Software Systems for Universal Self-Supervision
column5: Gaurab Banerjee
column6: Alex Tamkin, Shashank Rammoorthy, Vincent Liu
column7: Universal self-supervised (SSL) algorithms hold promise for making machine learning accessible to a range of high-impact domains, such as protein biology, manufacturing, and genomics. We present DABS 2.0: a set of improved datasets, algorithms, and software systems for advancing research on universal SSL. We extend the recently-introduced DABS benchmark with the addition of five real-world scientific domains: protein biology, bacterial genomics, multispectral satellite imagery, semiconductor wafers, and particle physics, bringing the total number of domains in the benchmark to twelve. We also propose a new universal SSL algorithm, Capri, and a generalized version of masked autoencoding, apply both on all twelve domains---the most wide-ranging exploration of SSL yet. We find that multiple algorithms show gains across all domains, outperforming previous baselines. In addition, we find that the optimal masking fraction varies based on the domain, and linear evaluator performance is not correlated with finetuning accuracy. We also present and open source our codebase, DABS-Launcher, which enables pretraining and transfer runs across all domains in <36 hours using compute resources that are free for academic researchers.

column5: Vivek Myers
column6: Erdem Biyik, Nima Anari, Dorsa Sadigh
column7: Learning from human feedback has been shown to be a useful approach in acquiring robot reward functions. However, expert feedback is often assumed to be drawn from an underlying unimodal reward function. This assumption does not always hold, including in settings where multiple experts provide data or when a single expert provides data for different tasks. We thus have to go beyond learning a unimodal reward and focus on learning a multimodal reward function. We formulate the multimodal reward learning as a mixture learning problem and develop a novel ranking-based learning approach, in which the experts are only required to rank a given set of trajectories. Furthermore, as access to interaction data is often expensive in robotics, we develop an active querying approach to accelerate the learning process. We conduct experiments and user studies using a multi-task variant of OpenAI's LunarLander and a real Fetch robot, where we collect data from multiple users with different preferences. The results suggest that our approach can efficiently learn multimodal reward functions, and improve data-efficiency over benchmark methods that we adapt to our learning problem.

column5: Evan Baldonado, Lan Jiang, Jasper McAvity
column7: FocusList is an an improved to-do list website to help you focus. When you have work to do, FocusList blocks distracting websites like social media. You can also import to-do list items from Google Calendar and Gmail.

column3: A Synapse Circuit for a Configurable Neuromorphic Neural Network Layer
column5: Malick Sere (student), Professor Sara Achour (Project advisor)
column7: Conventional machine learning is quite energy intensive. However, for some tasks, higher energy efficiency can be achieved using hardware that emulates the brain by encoding signals as sequences of spikes. Concepts for such hardware are generally inflexible, yielding fixed network topologies. We propose a synapse circuit that could enable a configurable network layer and characterize its robustness through system level simulation.

column3: Emulating Illusion Scaleup for Neural Network Applications​
column5: Ben Auslin
column7: The Illusion architecture is designed to run deep learning workloads with total energy and execution time near that of an ideal single chip. The scaleup project aims to demonstrate that the architecture can keep pace with growing neural network sizes while maintaining its low overheads. Ongoing verification of a new chip that will demonstrate scaleup involves emulating the design in hardware to accelerate logic simulations. Emulation will allow the development team to test scaling the system before fabricating the design.

column5: Bryce Hunt, Raymond Guo, David Witten, Roy Yuan
column7:
Almost everyone has considered joining a startup at one point in their career. However, the process is incredibly annoying. You have to:

go through job boards with thousands of company names you’ve never heard of
vet each startup’s funding + product + team background
then make sure your profile fits the exact tech stack that the startup is looking for
finally spend hours writing an application that will never get read
all the while you’re working a full-time job at your current company

We've almost entirely automated the job search process to be handled mostly over email, at scale. Given a shortlist of preferences, each user will be given the best matches that exactly match their skills and interests, with an 'easy-to-vet' process. These matches then directly lead to interviews and phone screens!

The app allows users to sell and buy high quality authentic clothing and ceremonial items. Especially since COVID many indigenous people have not been able to access ceremonial items without going to ceremony. Potecha offers a one stop shop for all ceremonial items from trusted community vendors. Unlike Facebook Marketplace, Potecha will target members of indigenous communites and provide a tailored experience to help community members find authentic clothing and items.

column7: Potecha offers a one stop shop for all ceremonial items from trusted community vendors. Unlike Facebook Marketplace, Potecha will target members of indiginous communites and provide a tailored experience to help community members find authentic clothing and items.

column4: Education, Virtual or Augmented Reality, Mobile
column5: Aaron Schultz, Laikh Tewari, Kimmy Chang, Michelle Xing, Ryota Eki
column7: Arla is a language learning app for iOS that uses augmented reality to help students learn vocabulary based on the objects in their everyday environment. The app allows students to translate an object simply by pointing their phone camera at it. Additional features include saving photos as flashcards and pronunciation help and testing.
